 Justification:
 FY 2027 Base procurement dollars in the amount of $54.363 million support obsolescence mitigation and other design modifications of the M142 High Mobility Artillery Rocket System (M142 HIMARS) fleet (MOD
 1), CFCS Mods (MOD 2), and APNT mods (MOD 3).

 MOD 1. FY 2027 HIMARS Modifications funding will include efforts such as: Interactive Electronic Technical Manuals (IETM) updates, Diagnostic Trainer and M142 HIMARS Mock-up Trainer updates, and
 system engineering modifications to the major M142 HIMARS components.

 MOD 2. FY 2027 continues the funding for MOD 2 (CFCS). Procures 46 CFCS retrofit kits and 6 CFCS Launcher Adapter Group (LAG) kits, to modernize the M142 HIMARS launcher fire control system to
 provide the capability to launch all current and future munitions and enable obsolescence mitigation. The LAGs are fielded at a three-to-one ratio of launchers-to-LAGs. The CFCS LAG Kit is a set of cables and
 adapters used to test the CFCS. To provide budget transparency, MOD 2 captures CFCS LAG kit purchases as a distinctive cost element under MOD 2 versus obsolescence mitigation measures associated with
 MOD 1.

 MOD 3. FY 2027 continues the MOD 3 (APNT update). Procures 46 DIGAR kits to protect fielded UFCS-equipped M142 HIMARS launchers from Global Positioning System (GPS) jamming and procures 16
 APNT Launcher Adapter Group (LAG) kits. These APNT LAG kits are an additional LAG component specific to UFCS DIGARS-equipped launchers and fielded at a nine-to-one ratio of launchers-to-LAGs. The
 APNT LAG Kit is a set of cables and adapters used to test the APNT. These LAG kits enable troubleshooting of DIGARS equipped UFCS M142 HIMARS. The modernized hardware (DIGAR) improves system
 robustness against the GPS jamming threat. Procurement of NavStrike-M facilitates compliance with statutory requirements and begins in FY 2027.

 HIMARS MODS Funding increase from FY 2026 to FY 2027 has no significant change.

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.




